04972nam a22006015i 9780773556201DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735562017 a10.1515/97807735562012doi  a(DE-B1597)657390  a(OCoLC)1076270076  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD1992b.D37 2018 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a338.109471 aDarrow, David W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTsardom of Sufficiency, Empire of Norms :bStatistics, Land Allotments, and Agrarian Reform in Russia, 1700-1921 /cDavid W. Darrow. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note about Translations, Transliterations, and Dates -- tThe New Land Allotment Tradition, the New Moral Economy -- tSetting the Precedent: The State of Sufficiency -- tSerf Emancipation: Sanctifying the Normed Nadel, Measuring Its Sufficiency -- tNormalizing the Nadel and Peasant Economy: History and Zemstvo Statistics -- t“Normal” Households: Economic Development and the Middle Peasant -- tStolypin’s Wager on the Middle: Land Norms and “Sufficiency” -- tLand Norms as Social Justice in Revolution, Civil War, and Beyond -- tThe Legacy of Serfdom and Persistence of the Sufficient Nadel -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat happens when you measure an economy? How does measurement impact policy? In Tsardom of Sufficiency, Empire of Norms David Darrow responds to these broad questions by looking at the application and profound consequences of statistical measurement to the peasant economy in Russia, from the eighteenth century to the Civil War. Nearly all studies of Russia make reference to the land allotment, or "nadel," as a measure of peasant wellbeing. This is the first work examining the origins of the nadel, how statistical measurement converted it into a modern entitlement, and how it framed the state–peasant relationship. Land, Darrow argues, was life – peasants needed it and the state, most everyone believed, had an obligation to provide it. The question, however, was how much land was enough. Statistics supplied the answer but also locked policy-makers and society into a particular way of seeing peasants and their economy. Even the empire's final attempt to reform the peasant economy after 1905 remained locked within the old regime category of the nadel. Statistical measurement strengthened, rather than weakened, the nadel as a category of peasant economic wellbeing such that it persisted beyond 1917 into the early years of Soviet power. Based on archival sources and rural councils' statistical studies, Tsardom of Sufficiency, Empire of Norms shows how the state constructed both an image and a measure of peasant wellbeing from which it could not escape, and how the resultant perception that peasants were entitled to a sufficient allotment became a major obstacle to successful agrarian reform.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgriculture and statezRussiaxHistory. 0aAgriculture and statezRussiaxStatisticsxHistory. 0aAllotment of landzRussiaxHistory. 0aAllotment of landzRussiaxStatisticsxHistory. 0aLand reformzRussiaxHistory. 0aPeasantsxGovernment policyzRussiaxHistory. 0aPeasantszRussiaxEconomic conditionsvStatistic. 0aPeasantszRussiaxStatisticsxEconomic conditions. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgr